com.vmware.vapi.std

Class Progress

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.vmware.vapi.std.Progress

  • public final class Progress
extends java.lang.Object
    Progress notification which is emitted by a running operation.

    Progress can be either determinate or indeterminate. Determinate progress gives an estimate of how much work is already done and how much more work remains. Indeterminate progress means that progress is being made but it is not clear how much more work remains. For determinate progress getMin() is strictly less than getMax() and getCurrent() is a value in the closed interval from getMin() to getMax(). For indeterminate progress getMin() must be equal to getMax() and getCurrent() is any non-negative value.

    The same determinate progress can be represented in multiple ways (all semantically equivalent). For example 50% progress can be represented as (min=0, max=100, current=50) or (min=0, max=10, current=5) or (min=0, max=4, current=2) etc.

    The order of progress notifications is not guaranteed. The consumer of progress notifications should ignore progress notifications that go backwards (i.e. decreasing current progress value).
